    "body": "<span class=\"solution-visible-txt\">All submissions for this problem are available.</span>Byteland is a 1D city located at the suburbs of Pune. And guess what! It's time for the Byteland Fest !!\n\nThere are **N** counters set up and each counter serves a different kind of sweet. \n**C<sub>i</sub>** -  the counter serving the sweet **i**, is defined by two things: a starting point **s<sub>i</sub>** and an ending point **e<sub>i</sub>**\n\nCounter **C<sub>i</sub>** spans the region from **s<sub>i</sub>** to **e<sub>i</sub>** (both inclusive)\n\nThe fest will be going on for **M** days. Each day, Shanu and his mom will be visiting a friend of theirs, at location **x**.\nHowever, Shanu has no interest in meeting friends, he's just craving to eat the sweets.\nHis craving is described by integer **k**, which is the minimum amount of different sweets he's dying to have on that day.\n\nBut poor Shanu, his mom doesn't like him roaming too far in the city. \nHence, she will allow him to roam around only in the region of length **l** with their current location (Shanu's friend's place) at centre.\nShanu needs to ask for his mom's permission to roam around in region of the minimum possible length **l**, such that he is able to eat atleast **k** different sweets.\n\nCan you help Shanu find the minimum length for each day so that he is able to enjoy atleast **k** sweets.\n\nNote: Shanu can taste sweet **i**, if and only if he can reach any point of the region spanned by counter **C<sub>i</sub>**.\n\n\n#### Input\n\n- First line of the input is a single integer **T** - number of testcases. Each Test case is described as:\n- First line of each test case has two integers - **N** and **M**.\n- This follows **N** lines, where i<sup>th</sup> line has two integers: **s<sub>i</sub>** and **e<sub>i</sub>**, starting and ending point of counter **C<sub>i</sub>**\n- This follows **M** lines, where i<sup>th</sup> line has two integers: **x** - (location of the place they visit on day **i**) and **k** - Shanu's craving on day **i**.\n\n#### Output\n- For each test case, output **M** lines:\n- Single integer **l<sub>i</sub>** on **i<sup>th</sup>** line: minimum length of the region Shanu can roam in to fulfill his craving on day **i**\n\n\n#### Constraints\n- 1 \u2264 T \u2264 10\n- 1 \u2264 k \u2264 N \u2264 10<sup>5</sup>\n- 1 \u2264 M \u2264 5 * 10<sup>4</sup>\n- -10<sup>9</sup> \u2264 s<sub>i</sub> \u2264 e<sub>i</sub> \u2264 10<sup>9</sup>\n- -10<sup>9</sup> \u2264 x \u2264 10<sup>9</sup>\n\n#### Example Inputs\n1 \n\n5 5 \n\n0 1 \n\n1 2 \n\n2 3 \n\n2 4 \n\n5 10 \n\n0 2 \n\n7 2 \n\n8 1 \n\n6 5 \n\n1 4\n\n#### Example Outputs\n2 \n\n6 \n\n0 \n\n10 \n\n2 \n\n#### Explanation\n**Query 1**: interval [-1, 1] of size 2 will overlap with two intervals - [0, 1] and [1, 2] \n\n**Query 2**: interval [4, 10] of size 2 will overlap with two intervals - [2, 4] and [5, 10] \n\n**Query 3**: interval [8, 8] of size 0 will overlap with 1 interval [1, 2] \n\n**Query 4**: interval [1, 11] of size 10 will overlap with all intervals. \n\n**Query 5**: interval [0, 2] of size 3 will overlap with 4 intervals - [0, 2], [1, 2], [2, 3] and [2, 4] \n",
